# EKS Workload Authentication & AWS Access - Quick Knowledge Share

## Core Components

```text
EKS Cluster
 ├─ Control Plane
 ├─ Worker Nodes
 ├─ Add-ons
 │   └─ EKS Pod Identity Agent
 ├─ Namespaces
 ├─ Service Accounts
 ├─ Pods / Deployments
 ├─ RBAC Roles & RoleBindings
 └─ Applications

AWS
 ├─ IAM Policies
 ├─ IAM Roles
 ├─ STS
 ├─ S3
 ├─ Secrets Manager
 ├─ DynamoDB
 ├─ SQS
 ├─ SNS
 ├─ RDS
 ├─ KMS
 └─ CloudWatch
```

---

## What is Each Component?

### IAM Policy

Defines permissions.

Examples:

* S3 Read/Write
* DynamoDB Access
* Secrets Manager Access
* SQS Access

Example:

```text
Allow:
  s3:GetObject
  s3:PutObject
```

---

### IAM Role

Container for permissions.

```text
IAM Role
    ↓
Attached Policies
```

Examples:

```text
s3-role
secret-reader-role
dynamodb-role
```

---

### Service Account (Kubernetes Identity)

Identity for Pods inside Kubernetes.

```text
Pod
 ↓
ServiceAccount
```

Examples:

```text
frontend-sa
backend-sa
reporting-sa
```

---

### Pod Identity Association

Maps:

```text
ServiceAccount
        ↓
IAM Role
```

Example:

```text
backend-sa
      ↓
backend-role
```

---

### Pod Identity Agent Add-on

Runs on worker nodes.

Responsibilities:

```text
Pod Starts
    ↓
Detect ServiceAccount
    ↓
Query EKS Mapping
    ↓
Call AWS STS
    ↓
Fetch Temporary Credentials
    ↓
Provide Credentials to Pod
```

---

### STS (Security Token Service)

Issues temporary credentials.

```text
Access Key
Secret Key
Session Token
```

No long-term credentials required.

---

